bib.title: Oxygen-16 Induced Fission Of 209-Bi At 89.5 Mev

free_txt: Radiochimica Acta Vol. 65, (1994) 9-11
Compiled by first author (Sarbjit Singh)
Decay-data wasn't mentioned in the article.

VS. Decay data corrected in 024.
Resolution of 2.0 keV at 1332 keV.
The errors listed are the standard deviations
between the results from five different irradiations
and different gamma rays used for the same nuclide.
Samples were irradiated for a suitable
length of time so as to determine both the short and
long lived fission products.
In each irradiation the decay of the gamma ray
peak of the fission products were followed for
suitable length of time so as to have minimum error
due to counting statistics.
The dead time correction at the amplifier stage for
the count rate was carried out using reference peak of
1368 keV of 24-Na.
The cumulative production cross section was determined
for most of the mass chains. In case of shielded nuclei
independent production cross section was determined.
In the case of 85m-Kr, 106m-Rh, 115g-Cd, 116m-In and
117m-Cd only one isomeric state was studied which
gives partial cross section for the nuclide.
Targets of super pure 209-Bi were prepared by vacuum
evaporation on 7.6 mumeter super pure aluminium
foil. Targets of 0.837 mg/cm**2 of bismuth were used
for Irradiation. In order to avoid the cross
contamination of fission products due to large activity
of direct reaction products, the 209-Bi target was
covered with a 0.76 mumeter super pure aluminium foil.
This will allow the fission products to pass and will
prevent the reaction products. The whole assembly was
put in a target holder and irradiated for a suitable
length of time with 96 MeV 16-O particle
beam of ~100 nano-ampere. The average incident 16-O
ion energy on the bismuth targets was 89.5 MeV,
whereas the average energy on the aluminium catcher
foil was 76.1 MeV.
Bismuth targets and aluminium catchers were
separated from each other carefully to avoid cross
contamination. Aluminium catchers were mounted
separately on perspex plates in suitable geometry for
gamma ray spectrometry using HPGe detector system.
